Requirements:
Admission to the Teacher Education Program (TEP) is prerequisite to enrollment in any professional studies course listed at the 300 or 400 level. Application for admission to the TEP is made by the student through the Office of Student Success in the College of Education and Human Sciences. A student is eligible to apply for admission to the TEP when the following requirements have been met:
1. A composite score of 21 or higher on the ACT (or 18-20 with a GPA of 3.00-3.24) or A concordant score of 1080 on the SAT (or 960-1070 with a GPA of 3.00-3.24);
2. A passing score on the basic skills assessment of the Alabama Educator Certification Assessment Program (AECAP), Praxis Core Academic Skills for Educators Tests, must be on file prior to admission to TEP. The basic skills assessment may be waived with a composite score of 24 or higher on the ACT or a concordant score of 1180 or higher on the SAT;
3. A minimum overall grade point average of 2.75 (or 2.50-2.74 with a GPA of 3.00-3.24 on the last 60 hours) on all college/university work;
4. Completion of a minimum of 48 semester hours of credit;
5. Completion of EN 111, EN 112, COM 201 or other approved speech course, and a general literature course;
6. Completion of the prescribed general studies courses in the teaching field;
7. A grade of C or better in all courses in the teaching field and professional studies, with no course in the teaching field taken more than twice;
8. Approval of the advisor and department chair;
9. Successful completion of an interview by a minimum of two full-time education faculty members with both recommending admission to the program;
10. A valid background clearance on file in the certification office.

To be admitted to the Teacher Education Program (TEP), a student must meet the following requirements:
1. An application for admission to the TEP submitted through the Office of Teacher Education Services via the student’s Banner account;
2. A minimum overall GPA of 2.75 on all coursework attempted at all institutions;
3. Successful completion of a general studies curriculum (at UNA or other institution) appropriate for the teaching field and degree sought (See specific program of study);
4. Successful completion of the following courses with a grade of C or better: EN 111, EN 112, COM 201; a literature sequence; a history sequence; ED 299 or HES 270; and EED 361 or EDF 375;
5. Verification of a passing score on the basic skills assessment of the Alabama Educator Certification Assessment Program (AECAP). This requirement is governed by the Alabama State Department of Education (ALSDE). Currently, the basic skills assessments are waived. However, candidates may submit a qualifying score on the ACT to meet this requirement. The qualifying score on the ACT is a composite score of 21. Candidates seeking admission to the TEP through the ACT WorkKeys assessment must pass all three sections of the assessment (Applied Math, Graphic Literacy, and Workplace Documents).
6. Completion of an interview with a committee of at least two members of the education faculty. Candidates must receive a positive recommendation;
7. Verification of background clearance through the ALSDE;
8. Proof of professional liability insurance;
9. A signed SOE Professional Dispositions form;
10. A signed Declaration of Constitutionality form.
